<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-369-062  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 369 062.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 16 1990 v9 n8 p50(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army's SMC held up again by bid probe. (Small Multiuser Computerprogram)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. ArmyInvestigationsMismanagementHardware SelectionMinicomputersUNIXGovernment Contracts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Army's SMC Held Up Again By Bid ProbeandM;The hard-luck saga of the Army's effort to buy 20,000 UNIX minicomputersystems continues.andM;The buy has been delayed for a second time while contracting officials makesure that one vendor's bid was not examined improperly by a competitor afterArmy employees shipped it to the competitor.andM;The mishandling of the document set back a contract award in the SmallMultiuser Computer (SMC) program for another four to eight weeks, said HelenGaramone, a spokeswoman for the Army's Information Systems Selection andAcquisition Agency (ISSAA).andP;  She said the delay would allow officials toinvestigate.andM;The procurement already was running six months behind schedule because of aprotest last year.andM;The events leading to the latest delay began a few months ago when a teamevaluating SMC offers at the Fort Huachuca, Ariz., headquarters of the Army'sInformation Systems Command misaddressed the documents, according to an Armyofficial who demanded anonymity.andM;Officials would not identify the companies involved in the snafu.andP;  Garamonesaid the vendor that received the box of documents &quot;contacted ISSAA withinminutes of discovering the problem and cooperated fully with theinvestigation.&quot;andM;&quot;[Officials] initiated the investigation because our first concern was toprotect the integrity of the process,&quot; Garamone said.andP;  &quot;It was not clear atfirst what happened.&quot;andM;ISSAA officials have met with the vendor to whom the documents belonged andhave taken sworn statements from those who received the box.andP;  Officials alsowere in contact with all other competing vendors.andM;Although investigators have not delivered a final repot, &quot;it's clear thatwhat happened was an accident,&quot; Garamone said.andP;  ISSAA officials &quot;aresatisfied that no harm was done to the integrity of the procurement,&quot; shesaid.andM;The award in the $500 million buy of 32-bit, 16-user systems at one time wasscheduled for last year and then delayed to May.andP;  The award now is postponedto June or July, Garamone said.andP;  The SMC buy will replace a 1985 contract forIntel Corp. 310 minicomputers and Wang Laboratories Inc. front-endmicrocomputers that expired earlier this year, officials have said.andM;Last year, the Army withstood a protest of the SMC request for proposals whenthe General Services Administration Board of Contract Appeals dismissed avendor's claim that maintenance provisions of the RFP were restrictive.andO;</TEXT></DOC>